fr:mainmatter.html:p:
Let E_{n} be a countable collection of countably infinite sets. Then
S=\bigcup ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}
is countably infinite.

We form the countably infinite family E_{n}=\{z/n\in \mathbb {Q}\mid  z\in \mathbb {Z},\gcd (z,n)=1\} where n\in \mathbb {N} is a positive integer. Each member is bijective with the integers, which is countably infinite. Then
S=\bigcup ^{\infty }_{n=1}E_{n}
is countably infinite by Cantor's diagonal argument, and S bijective to the set \mathbb {Q}. Hence \mathbb {Q} is countably infinite.
